ce:section.ce:para:
Dispersants are amphiphilic surfactants with dispersing functions, whose structure includes anchoring segments and chain segments [40,41]. The anchoring segment may adsorb the particles and improve particle dispersibility while the chain segment may dissolve in the medium, reducing the system interface energy. In this work, polyelectrolyte dispersant-poly (maleic acid-co-acrylic acid) sodium salt (PMAS, 
                        Figure S1
                     ) is introduced to facilitate the mild preparation of the CQDs-NH2 nanomaterial separation membrane for the first time. The novel membrane formation strategy possesses the following advantages. Considering the negatively charged substrate surface and positively charged CQDs-NH2, the polyelectrolyte-PMAS was used to strengthen the electrostatic force between CQDs-NH2 and substrate and promote the deposition of CQDs-NH2. The PMAS may come into the substrate pores first for its surfactant property, forming an electric double layer, strengthening the electrostatic force between CQDs-NH2 and substrate, and accelerating the particle deposition. The increased CQDs-NH2 may offer more -NH2 to react with trimesoyl chloride (TMC) to form an intact separation layer (Fig. 1
                     ). Besides, the PMAS anchoring segments may be conjunct with the adjacent distant CQDs-NH2 colloidal particles and weaken the long-range force, making the CQDs-NH2 distribution uniform and accelerating the membrane-forming efficiency. The room-temperature prepared CQDs-NH2 membrane showed high water permeance (55 L/m2·h1·bar1) and satisfied separation property to the NaCl/reactive black 5 mixture, showing great potential in molecular separation and resource recovery. This work may offer valuable insights into the facile preparation of nanomaterial separation membranes.

The porous polyethersulfone (PES) UF substrate (permeance: ∼600 L/m2·h1·bar1; mean pore size: ∼28 nm) and CQDs-NH2 solution (
                           Figure S2
                        ) were obtained according to our previous studies [42,43]. Trimesoyl chloride (TMC, 98%, Aladdin) was deployed to react with CQDs-NH2 to form separation layer. The deionized (DI) water and n-hexane (AR, Meryer (Shanghai) Chemical Technology Co., Ltd.) were used as aqueous and organic phase solvents separately. The poly (maleic acid-co-acrylic acid) sodium salt (PMAS, technical grade) purchased from Shandong Xintai Water Treatment Technology Co., Ltd was used as the polyelectrolyte surfactant to regulate the membrane formation process. Sodium sulfate (Na2SO4, AR), sodium chloride (NaCl, ≥99.5%), magnesium sulfate (MgSO4, AR), magnesium chloride (MgCl2, AR), indigo carmine (IC, 466.35 g·mol−1, ≥BS), reactive blue 19 (RB19, 626.54 g·mol−1, ≥AR), congo red (CR, 696.68 g·mol−1, BS), and reactive black 5 (RB5, 991.82 g·mol−1, ≥50%) were purchased from Sinopharm Chemical Reagent Co., Ltd to test the membrane separation performance and evaluate the CQDs-NH2 membrane-formation property. The detailed properties are listed in Table S1.

The weak binding force between CQDs-NH2 and the substrate with the weak reactivity between CQDs-NH2 and TMC jointly results in poor membrane formation properties (Fig. 2
                        &3). The dispersant-PMAS possesses anchoring segments and chain segments (
                           Figure S1
                        ). It can improve the particle dispersing behavior and lower the interfacial tension simultaneously. Herein, the PMAS was incorporated into the CQDs-NH2 aqueous solution to strengthen the electrostatic force between CQDs-NH2 particles and substrate pores and regulate the CQDs-NH2/TMC membrane formation process. The effects of CQDs-NH2/PMAS immersion time and TMC reaction time on membrane performance were evaluated (Fig. 4
                        ). Due to the negatively charged surface, the MgSO4 rejection of the CxTy membranes increased with the CQDs-NH2 deposition amounts and TMC reaction time increasing (Fig. 2
                        &3). The dispersant-PMAS possessing anchoring and chain segments (
                           Figure S1
                        ) showed negatively charged properties. Therefore, we chose Na2SO4 to study the separation performance of the P-CxTy membranes. The mixture of CQDs-NH2 and PMAS may coagulate with the condition of 3 wt% CQDs-NH2 and 0.2 wt% PMAS, but it remained stable mixed with other CQDs-NH2 concentrations (including 1 wt%, 2 wt%, 4 wt%, 5 wt%). The lab-synthesized CQDs-NH2 with 3–8 nm diameter distribution dispersing in water showed positively charged (∼17 mV) properties. The polyelectrolyte PMAS was negatively charged (∼15 mV). The coagulation may be rationalized by the equal charge between CQDs-NH2 and PMAS. Considering that high CQDs-NH2 concentration may cause aggregation and it is wasteful after the CQDs-NH2/PMAS immersion step was finished, we took a moderate 4 wt% CQDs-NH2 concentration for investigation. Surprisingly, we found that the membrane prepared at the condition of short immersion time (2.5 min) and TMC reaction (1 min) showed > 20% Na2SO4 (1000 ppm) rejection. The membrane showed high Na2SO4 rejection (nearly 80%) when increasing the immersion time of the aqueous solution and TMC solution. Besides, the water permeance of the P-C2.5Ty membrane keeps stable with enhanced Na2SO4 rejection when prolonging the reaction time from 1 to 7 min, meaning that the reaction between CQDs-NH2 and TMC may finish within 1 min. The improved Na2SO4 rejection may be rationalized by the negatively charged surface by -COCl hydrolysis. The experiments proved that the addition of PMAS boosts the reaction between CQDs-NH2 and TMC to form an intact selective layer.

However, with the CQDs-NH2/PMAS immersion time ranging from 2.5 to 10 min, the membrane permeance increased first and then decreased. The CQDs-NH2/PMAS immersion time affects the CQDs-NH2 deposition amounts directly, which in turn influences the membrane-formation property. Hence, the SEM was used to observe the CQDs-NH2 deposition process (Fig. 5
                        ). All Cx membranes showed general polymeric membrane morphologies after the pure CQDs-NH2/H2O solution was immersed (Fig. 5a). After the PMAS was introduced, the P-Cx membrane surfaces started to show irregular protruding structures (Fig. 5c). These protrude first become larger (7.5 min) and then exhibit uniform structures (10 min). The results strongly proved that the PMAS addition changed the CQDs-NH2 deposition behavior. The PES substrate surface shows ∼ 6.07 ± 0.32 nm roughness (
                           Figure S3
                        ). After the IP reaction, the CxT1 and P-CxT1 membrane surface roughness shows a similar tendency. The CxT1 membrane surface roughness increased from 7.99 to 8.34 nm and then decreased to 3.08 nm (Fig. 6

                        ). The P-CxT1 membranes decreased to 4.64 nm and then increased to 6.18 nm. Hence, the high permeance of the P-C5T1 membrane may ascribe to the large transport area caused by the increased roughness. The CxT1 and P-CxT1 membrane surfaces exhibited smooth morphology and roughness (Fig. 5
                        &6), which may be rationalized by the self-inhibiting process of CQDs-NH2 and TMC at the interface [45]. All P-CxT1 membranes showed the peak belongs to -NH-CO-, proving the successful reaction between -NH2 of CQDs-NH2 and TMC (
                           Figure S4
                        ).

Based on the surface charge variations, the membrane surface group compositions were analyzed by the XPS spectrum (Table 1
                        ). Taking CQDs-NH2 as the only amine source in the IP reaction, all membranes showed the N elements. It proved that the CQDs-NH2 were introduced on the membrane surfaces successfully. The testing trace amounts of Na are within error. After the PMAS was introduced, the P-CxT1 membranes exhibits more N amounts compared with the CxT1 membranes, and the amounts of Na of the P-CxT1 membrane surfaces increased. It proved that the PMAS was introduced into the separation layer or affected the reaction between CQDs-NH2 and TMC. The detailed N-group components were obtained by the deconvolution analysis (Fig. 9
                        ). The proportion of three N-containing groups was calculated from the integral area (Table 2
                        ). The CQDs-NH2 contains three groups, -NH2, -NH-, and -N-. Hence, it is irrational to judge the reaction degree by the deconvolution analysis data. But we may deduce whether the reaction happens or not by the relative contents. The -NH2 should increase with the aqueous time prolonging in theory. However, the -NH2 amount first increased from 39.41% to 50.19% and then decreased to 41.57% along with the aqueous immersion time. The -NH- amounts decreased from 50.77 to 45.20 first, and then it increased to 48.99%, indicating that the CQDs-NH2 reaction degree was decreased and then down. The P-C5T1 membrane showed the lowest reaction degree, which is corresponding with the membrane separation performance shown in Fig. 4.

The separation performance of the NF membrane is precise separation at the molecule scale makes great significance in resource recovery applications. The prepared P-C5T1 membrane exhibited low Na2SO4 rejection, which is expected to achieve salt and dye separation. Hence, we further tested the membrane separation performance of dyes with different molecular weights and structures (Fig. 11
                        ). The P-C5T1 membrane showed high rejections to CR and RB5. In the dye industry, NaCl is consumed massively with reactive dyes to improve the dyeing effects. Hence, we tested the membrane separation property towards the mixture of NaCl and RB5 to evaluate the membrane application potential in the dye industry. Compared to rejections to single solutes, the membrane showed slightly decreased RB5 rejection (90%) and increased NaCl rejection (10%). It may be caused by the interaction between the reactive dyes and NaCl, which is consistent with the previous reports [52]. In the first stage, the membrane permeance was first decreased due to the cake layer formation by dye deposition. After the cake layer formation was complete, the membrane performance became stable (17 L/m2·h1·bar1), exhibiting relatively high permeance and separation efficiency. Through comprehensive comparison with literature, the membrane fabricated from this study (Table 3
                        ) stands out for (1) mild and facile preparation process: facile interfacial polymerization method at room temperature without any assistant reagents or instruments; (2) excellent membrane-forming performance: the PMAS incorporation shorten the CQDs-NH2 uniform deposition process within 2.5 min and accelerate the CQDs-NH2 membrane-forming efficiency with high performance. This work has provided a successful protocol to prepare nanomaterial separation membranes at room temperature with low cost and a simple preparation method. It shows the possibility to promote the nanomaterial separation membranes to commercial development.
